51. What is an event listener?

An event listener is a function that waits for a specific event to occur on an element. When the event happens, the listener executes a predefined action. Event listeners are commonly added using the addEventListener() method.

52. Explain event bubbling.

Event bubbling is a process where an event starts on the target element and then propagates upward through its parent elements. It allows parent elements to respond to events triggered by child elements. This behavior is useful for event delegation.

53. What is DOM manipulation?

DOM manipulation is the process of modifying HTML elements using JavaScript. Developers can add, remove, update, or style elements dynamically. This allows web pages to change without being reloaded.

54. Explain the difference between innerHTML and textContent.

innerHTML allows developers to read or modify HTML content, including tags. textContent works only with plain text and ignores HTML tags. Using textContent is generally safer when displaying user input.

55. What is form validation?

Form validation is the process of checking whether user input meets specific requirements before submission. It helps prevent invalid or incomplete data from being sent. Validation improves both security and user experience.

56. Explain client-side validation and server-side validation.

Client-side validation is performed in the user’s browser before data is sent to the server. Server-side validation occurs on the server after submission and provides stronger security. Most applications use both methods together.

57. What is localStorage?

localStorage is a browser feature that stores data permanently on a user’s device. The data remains available even after the browser is closed. It is commonly used for saving user preferences and settings.

58. What is sessionStorage?

sessionStorage stores data only for the duration of a browser session. Once the browser tab is closed, the stored data is removed. It is useful for temporary information that should not persist.

59. What is asynchronous programming?

Asynchronous programming allows tasks to run without blocking the execution of other code. It is especially useful for operations such as network requests and file loading. This approach improves application performance and responsiveness.

60. Explain callbacks in JavaScript.

A callback is a function passed as an argument to another function. It is executed after a specific task has been completed. Callbacks are commonly used in asynchronous programming.
61. What is a Promise?

A Promise is an object that represents the eventual result of an asynchronous operation. It can be in one of three states: pending, fulfilled, or rejected. Promises make asynchronous code easier to read and manage compared to nested callbacks.

62. Explain async/await.

async and await are features built on top of Promises that simplify asynchronous programming. The async keyword declares a function that returns a Promise, while await pauses execution until the Promise is resolved. This makes asynchronous code look more like regular synchronous code.

63. What is an API?

An API (Application Programming Interface) is a set of rules that allows different software applications to communicate with each other. APIs enable systems to exchange data and functionality without exposing internal implementation details. They are widely used in web and mobile applications.

64. What is the Fetch API?

The Fetch API is a modern JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests. It allows developers to send requests to servers and handle responses using Promises. Fetch is commonly used to retrieve data from APIs and update web pages dynamically.

65. Explain HTTP status codes.

HTTP status codes are numerical responses sent by a server to indicate the result of a request. For example, 200 means the request was successful, 404 means the requested resource was not found, and 500 indicates a server error. These codes help developers understand and troubleshoot communication between clients and servers.

66. What is the difference between frontend and backend development?

Frontend development focuses on the visual and interactive parts of a website that users see and use directly. Backend development handles server-side logic, databases, authentication, and data processing. Together, frontend and backend create complete web applications.

67. Explain the concept of Single Page Applications (SPA).

A Single Page Application (SPA) loads a single HTML page and updates content dynamically without reloading the entire page. This creates a faster and smoother user experience. Popular frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue are often used to build SPAs.

68. What are the main advantages of modular JavaScript?

Modular JavaScript divides code into separate, reusable modules. This improves code organization, readability, maintainability, and scalability. It also allows multiple developers to work on different parts of a project more efficiently.

69. What is Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)?

Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a security vulnerability that allows attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages. These scripts can steal user information, modify content, or perform unauthorized actions. Proper input validation and output encoding help prevent XSS attacks.

70. Explain the importance of website performance optimization.

Website performance optimization improves loading speed, responsiveness, and overall user experience. Faster websites reduce bounce rates and improve search engine rankings. Optimization techniques include image compression, caching, code minification, and reducing unnecessary network requests.